As a side note I'll also add that xmlm's handling of namespaces is =20
going to keep attributes of the xmlns namespace instead of removing =20
them. This allows to know which prefix bindings were done in the =20
document. Given how output is going to work chaining xmlm's input with =20=

output  you'll get the same prefixes that were present on input =20
(provided the same ns is not bound to two different prefixes in a =20
given context in which case there may be differences).

